        <p><em>Last fact-verified 23 April 2026</em></p>

        <h2>FAQ</h2>

        <h3>How long is the Mornington Peninsula?</h3>
        <p>About 40 km from north to south, and about 20 km wide at its broadest. At the Tip (Portsea / Point Nepean) it narrows to a few hundred metres. It is much longer than it appears on a map of Victoria.</p>

        <h3>What are the four subregions of the Mornington Peninsula?</h3>
        <p>Hinterland (wine country ridges around Red Hill), Bay Coast (calm bay beaches from Mornington to Dromana), Sorrento to the Tip (dramatic coastal villages from Blairgowrie to Portsea), and Ocean &amp; Western Port (wild beaches around Cape Schanck, Flinders, and Balnarring).</p>

        <h3>What is the difference between the bay side and the ocean side of the Peninsula?</h3>
        <p>The bay side (Port Phillip Bay) is calm, warm, and sheltered — safe for family swimming. The ocean side (Bass Strait) receives open-ocean swells. Rips are present and currents are strong. Do not treat them as comparable.</p>

        <h3>How far is Sorrento from Red Hill?</h3>
        <p>About 30–35 minutes by car. They feel close on the map but are on opposite sides of the Peninsula with winding hinterland roads between them.</p>

        <h3>Can you do the whole Mornington Peninsula in one day trip?</h3>
        <p>You can visit one subregion properly. Two is possible if you plan carefully. Visiting all four subregions in a single day is not realistic without spending most of it in the car.</p>
